<template id="tpl-awardco">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-tag">Case Study · Internship · Summer 2025</div>
    <h1 class="page-title">Employee Recognition Platform at Awardco</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">A 6-week UX sprint redesigning employee recognition workflows to increase genuine engagement — under NDA constraints.</p>
    <div class="page-meta-row">
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Role</div><div class="page-meta-value">UX Designer & Researcher</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Duration</div><div class="page-meta-value">6 Weeks (Summer Sprint)</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Impact</div><div class="page-meta-value">Won Creativity Award</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Constraint</div><div class="page-meta-value">NDA — Limited visuals</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">Understanding the Problem</h2>
    <div class="page-callout">"What would make a user want to create content — not just feel forced to?"</div>
    <p class="page-body">We kicked off with team discussions around two key questions: what can a user consume that would make them want to create (post)? And what would make them want to claim rewards? To better understand the problem, our team created user journey maps to visualize scenarios where users interacted with the platform.</p>
    <p class="page-body">One journey involved an employee being asked to recognize a colleague but feeling unmotivated to do so. We asked ourselves: how might we increase user engagement and curiosity beyond that single task?</p>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">User Journeys — John & June</h2>
    <img id="awardco-whiteboard" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="John and June user journey whiteboard" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-bottom:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
    <div class="page-two-col">
      <div class="page-card">
        <div class="page-card-label">John — "I Got Forced 2 Do This, Why?"</div>
        <div class="page-card-body">Manager tells John to recognize a colleague → logs into platform → recognizes someone → goes to feed to validate → positive reinforcement / impact score → notices he's close to next milestone → CTA to recognize again → 🎉 confetti</div>
      </div>
      <div class="page-card">
        <div class="page-card-label">June — "I Want to See What Can Be Done"</div>
        <div class="page-card-body">Gets email notification → logs in → sees recognition + 10 points → sees what she can get / discounted rewards → redeems → share redemption (who helped, what is it, do you like it?) → go to feed to see what others are doing</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">My Design Approach</h2>
    <img id="awardco-sketch" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Early sketches and wireframes" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-bottom:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
    <p class="page-body">As someone newer to UX at the time, I faced a steep learning curve — but approached it with curiosity and commitment. Due to a signed NDA, I'm only able to show limited project details or visuals, but I'll walk through my role and process. Despite limited access to the existing Awardco UI, I focused on:</p>
    <div class="page-steps">
      <div class="page-step"><span class="page-step-num">01</span><div><strong>Listing key features</strong> users might need or expect</div></div>
      <div class="page-step"><span class="page-step-num">02</span><div><strong>Sketching initial ideas</strong> and layout possibilities on paper</div></div>
      <div class="page-step"><span class="page-step-num">03</span><div><strong>Iterating quickly</strong> into lo-fi wireframes using Figma</div></div>
      <div class="page-step"><span class="page-step-num">04</span><div><strong>Testing concepts</strong> internally with Awardco employees</div></div>
    </div>
    <img id="awardco-wireframe2" src="" alt="Wireframe sketches and notes" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-top:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">Team Collaboration & Growth</h2>
    <img id="awardco-notes" src="" alt="Team brainstorm notes" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-bottom:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
    <p class="page-body">Working with a more experienced team challenged me in the best ways. I had to quickly adapt to UX-specific terminology and workflows, fast-paced brainstorming sessions, and stakeholder expectations. There were moments of doubt, especially when feedback was tough or ideas didn't land — but I learned to ask better questions, embrace critique, and refine my communication.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">Final Design Solution</h2>
    <p class="page-body">We designed a streamlined recognition experience with clear visual hierarchy, engaging animations, and social features that encourage peer-to-peer recognition.</p>
    <div class="page-two-col" style="margin-top:16px">
      <img id="awardco-award-team" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="The Creativity Award — team recognition screen" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
      <img id="awardco-award-silly" src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="The Silly Goose Award — individual recognition screen" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.08)"/>
    </div>
    <p class="page-body" style="margin-top:14px;font-size:13px;color:rgba(20,30,60,0.45);font-style:italic;">Left: Team Creativity Award announcement with multiple winners. Right: Individual "Silly Goose" award with fun, personalized copy — showing the range of recognition styles we designed.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">Key Design Features</h2>
    <div class="page-feature-grid">
      <div class="page-feature"><div class="page-feature-title">Visual Recognition</div><div class="page-feature-body">Prominent award announcements with trophy iconography and celebratory design elements to make recognition feel special and memorable.</div></div>
      <div class="page-feature"><div class="page-feature-title">Social Engagement</div><div class="page-feature-body">Integrated comment system and reaction features (Fly the W, Level Up, A-Game) to build community around recognition.</div></div>
      <div class="page-feature"><div class="page-feature-title">Impact Scores & Milestones</div><div class="page-feature-body">Gamification through milestone tracking — users could see how close they were to the next level, nudging continued engagement.</div></div>
      <div class="page-feature"><div class="page-feature-title">Personalized Copy</div><div class="page-feature-body">Each award type had distinct tone and personality — from serious team achievements to playful individual shoutouts like the Silly Goose Award.</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">Outcome</h2>
    <div class="page-callout-success">🏆 The UX Team won "The Creativity Award" — nominated by Adam (Admin) for outstanding creativity, innovative thinking, and raising the creative bar for the entire team.</div>
    <p class="page-body">This sprint taught me the importance of clear communication in a team setting, designing under real-world constraints, listening to both users and teammates, and the value of iterating quickly under pressure. Working at Awardco helped me grow in professional collaboration — it challenged me to work fast, learn new tools, and adopt quickly.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="page-tools-row">
    <span class="page-tool">Figma</span><span class="page-tool">FigJam</span><span class="page-tool">Notion</span><span class="page-tool">Discord / Slack</span>
  </div>
</template>

<template id="tpl-craigslist">
  <div class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-tag">Case Study · Concept · UX + Gamification</div>
    <h1 class="page-title">Middle Earth — Shire Quest Pass</h1>
    <p class="page-subtitle">A gamified mobile experience that transforms a visit to the Hobbiton Movie Set into an interactive adventure — with character selection, QR quests, XP rewards, and real-world collectibles.</p>
    <div class="page-meta-row">
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Role</div><div class="page-meta-value">UX Designer</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Type</div><div class="page-meta-value">MVP Concept</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Setting</div><div class="page-meta-value">Hobbiton Movie Set, NZ</div></div>
      <div class="page-meta-item"><div class="page-meta-label">Tools</div><div class="page-meta-value">Figma</div></div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">The Opportunity</h2>
    <p class="page-body">Hobbiton Movie Set draws over 600,000 annual visitors and generates NZ$630M in film tourism spending. But the experience ends at the tour. The Shire Quest Pass turns passive visitors into active adventurers — increasing engagement, exploration time, and per-visitor spending through a layered quest system.</p>
    <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Shire Quest Pass MVP concept — Hobbiton Movie Set" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-bottom:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.06)"/>
    <div class="page-two-col">
      <div class="page-card"><div class="page-card-label">Scale</div><div class="page-card-body">600k annual visitors · NZ$630M tourism spend · 280 on-site employees · 10–20% of NZ tourists motivated by film attractions.</div></div>
      <div class="page-card"><div class="page-card-label">The Problem</div><div class="page-card-body">A visit to Hobbiton is memorable but passive. There's no system to drive deeper exploration, repeat engagement, or spending beyond the base ticket.</div></div>
    </div>
    <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="Economic impact of film tourism statistics" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-top:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.06)"/>
  </div>

  <div class="page-section">
    <h2 class="page-section-title">How the Experience Works</h2>
    <p class="page-body">Visitors purchase a Quest Pass alongside their ticket. They download the app, choose a character, and the Shire becomes a living quest map.</p>
    <img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," alt="How the Shire Quest Pass experience works — flow diagram" style="width:100%;border-radius:10px;margin-bottom:16px;border:1px solid rgba(20,30,60,0.06)"/>
